{"title_page": "1997 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=June 2019|bot=noref (GreenC bot)}}\n{{Infobox Football All-Ireland\n |image    = \n |year     = 1997\n |dates    = 11 May 1997 \u2013 28 September 1997\n |teams    = 32\n |team     = Kerry\n |titles   = 31st\n |captain  = [[Liam Hassett]]\n |manager  = [[P\u00e1id\u00ed \u00d3 S\u00e9]]\n |team2    = Mayo\n |captain2 = [[Noel Connelly]]\n |manager2 = [[John Maughan]]\n |munster  = Kerry\n |leinster = Offaly\n |ulster   = Cavan\n |connacht = Mayo\n |poty     = [[File: Colours of Kerry.svg|border|20px]] [[Maurice Fitzgerald (footballer)|Maurice Fitzgerald]]\n |topscorer= [[File: Colours of Kerry.svg|border|20px]] [[Maurice Fitzgerald (footballer)|Maurice Fitzgerald]] (0-28)\n |matches  = \n |previous = [[1996 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1996]]\n |next     = [[1998 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship|1998]]\n|}}\nThe '''1997 Bank of Ireland [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]]''' was the 111th staging of the All-Ireland Senior Football Championship, the [[Gaelic Athletic Association]]'s premier inter-county [[Gaelic football]] tournament. The championship began on 11 May 1997 and ended on 28 September 1997.\n\n[[Meath GAA|Meath]] entered the championship as the defending champions; however, they were defeated by [[Offaly GAA|Offaly]] in the Leinster final.\n\nOn 28 September 1997 [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]], the most successful county in Gaelic football history, claimed their 31st All-Ireland title - and their first since 1986 - with a 0-13 to 1-7 victory over [[Mayo GAA|Mayo]].\n\nThis year also saw Ulster's most successful county, [[Cavan GAA|Cavan]], win their first [[Ulster Senior Football Championship|provincial title]] since 1969.\n\n==Munster Championship format change==\nA new 2 year system was introduced in Munster meaning that [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]], [[Cork GAA|Cork]] & [[Clare GAA|Clare]] would have straight access to the Munster semi-finals  for [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]], [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]] & [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]] would play in a Preliminary Round and the bye team in a lone Quarter final involved.\n\n==Fixtures and results==\n\n===[[Munster Senior Football Championship]]===   \n\n'''Preliminary round'''\n\n{{footballbox collapsible \n| date       = 11 May 1997\n| round      = Preliminary round\n| team1      = [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]]\n| score      = 1-13 - 0-16\n| team2      = [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]]\n| goals1     = D Ryan 0-5, J Quane 1-1, M Galvin 0-3, Damien Reidy 0-2, D Fitzgibbon 0-1, N Frewen 0-1.\n| goals2     = D Browne 0-7, P Lambert 0-4, D Foley 0-3, S Owens 0-1, B Burke 0-1.\n| stadium    = [[Gaelic Grounds]], [[Limerick]]\n| referee    = N Barrett ([[County Cork|Cork]])\n| attendance = \n| stack      = yes\n}}\n{{footballbox collapsible \n| date       = 18 May 1997\n| round      = Preliminary round replay\n| team1      = [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]]\n| score      = 1-17 - 2-8\n| team2      = [[Limerick GAA|Limerick]]\n| goals1     = B Cummins 0-8, J Owens 1-1, D Browne 0-2, D Foley 0-2, B Burke 0-1, M Sheehan 0-1, J Williams 0-1, S Maher 0-1.\n| goals2     = Damien Reidy 1-1, J Quane 1-0, P Galvin 0-3, I Walsh 0-2, D Rayn 0-1, N frewen 0-1.\n| stadium    = [[Clonmel GAA Ground|Ned Hall Park]], [[Clonmel]]\n| referee    = N Barrett ([[County Cork|Cork]])\n| attendance = \n| stack      = yes\n}} \n\n'''Quarter-final'''\n\n{{footballbox collapsible \n| date       = 1 June 1997\n| round      = Quarter-final\n| team1      = [[Waterford GAA|Waterford]]\n| score      = 1-5 - 2-7 \n| team2      = [[Tipperary GAA|Tipperary]]\n| goals1     = G Keane 1-2, O Costelloe 0-2, S Bergin 0-1.\n| goals2     = B Cummins 1-2, D Foley 1-0, M Sheehan 0-1, B Burke 0-1, J Williams 0-1, J Owens 0-1, D O'Connor 0-1.\n| stadium    = [[Fraher Field]], [[Dungarvan]]\n| referee    = W O'Mahony ([[Limerick]]) \n| attendance = \n| stack      = yes\n}}\n\n'''Semi-finals'''\n\n{{footballbox collapsible \n| date 